neral\" and free of templates in the WikiLogic pipeline [Q35].\nThe dataset steers clear of biases related to race, ethnicity, gender, sexuality, nationality,\nclass, and religion [Q47], and stories that contained strongly opinionated language or identity-\nbased biases were removed [Q127]. Stories not reflective of well-established scientific,\nhistorical, or legal facts were rewritten [Q126]. However, the authors accept certain\n\"psychologically fundamental generalizations\" (e.g., \"Covid is transmitted through the air\")\nthat add logical nuance but may not be factually invariant [Q128]. A downstream contamination\nconcern is noted: WikiLogic examples, being derived from real-world topics, may overlap with LLM\npretraining data [Q104], while HybLogic's template origin may allow fine-tuned models to learn\nstructural patterns [Q105].\n\n### Input Form\n**This is the highest-priority validity dimension for the lab's deployment.** FOLIO's inputs are\nfundamentally natural-language-first: each story consists of NL premise sets and NL conclusions\n[Q64], with parallel FOL annotations written alongside each sentence [Q65, Q37]. NL and FOL\nrepresentations are designed to be logically and semantically equivalent [Q68], and the dataset\nfollows FOL syntax standard in the AI/education community [Q52]. The NL layer was carefully\nengineered for grammatical naturalness (grammar-checked via Grammarly and reviewed by English\nLiterature specialists [Q49, Q50]) and designed to eliminate NL ambiguity where possible [Q51].\nSpecific NL conventions govern quantifier phrasing [Q132, Q133] and disjunction encoding\n[Q130, Q131], while FOL-level conventions address predicate properties (transitivity, symmetry\n[Q56]) and abstraction choices (tense neglected, plural verb forms removed [Q147]). The paper\ndirectly tests the impact of input format on performance and finds that adding FOL to the input\nimproves GPT-4 but not GPT-3.5 [Q162, Q163], confirming that input format materially affects\nbenchmark scores. This creates a live mismatch concern for labs considering a pure-symbolic\nevaluation regime: FOLIO was designed and validated for NL-first presentation, and scores under\na purely symbolic FOL presentation may not generalize from or to FOLIO's documented score\ndistributions. AST diversity also differs by subcorpus (WikiLogic: 53 ASTs; HybLogic: 33 ASTs)\n[Q106], affecting structural variety in the symbolic layer.\n\n### Output Ontology\nFOLIO uses a three-way truth-value label scheme — True, False, and Unknown — applied to each\nconclusion given its premise set [Q36, Q66]. This taxonomy maps cleanly onto standard NLI\ncategories (entailment / contradiction / neutral) with no residual ambiguity, as confirmed by\nthe deployment elicitation. Ground-truth labels are not determined by annotator judgment but are\nformally verified by an automated FOL inference engine that returns a definite answer for each\nconclusion [Q2, Q70]. FOL is explicitly preferred over NL as the grounding representation\nprecisely because \"FOL has no ambiguity while ambiguity can occur at various levels of NLP\"\n[Q137]. The majority baseline in the test set is 38.5%, reflecting a near-balanced three-class\ndistribution (87 True, 78 False, 61 Unknown) [Q94], with approximately 5% of conclusions having\ncomplex syntactic structures that pose comprehension challenges even for GPT-4 [Q120].\nThe output ontology explicitly excludes temporal and modal logic sub-categories [Q139, Q140],\nwhich the deployment has independently confirmed as out of scope.\n\n### Output Content\nGround-truth labels in FOLIO are anchored in objective logical validity rather than subjective\nannotator agreement: FOL annotations are verified by an automated inference engine that\noutputs whether each conclusion is True, False, or Unknown based on the premises [Q153]. This\neliminates annotator subjectivity as a source of label noise for the primary reasoning task. The\nannotation pipeline enforced strict separation of NL quality review (NLP/computational linguistics\nexperts only) from FOL quality review (FOL experts only) [Q29, Q124, Q125], and a standardized\nFOL annotation protocol was designed to ensure consistent, non-equivalent translations across\nexamples [Q54]. A thorough quality control pass found 39.2% of stories had at least one issue\nand were rewritten [Q48], and an additional FOL consistency QA round was added after preliminary\ninvestigations revealed inconsistencies in human-written formulas [Q53]. Commonsense premises\nrequired for logical closure were added explicitly at the alignment stage [Q55]. Human baseline\nanalysis confirms that expert annotators (CS students familiar with FOL) achieved 95.98%\naccuracy while non-experts achieved only 61.82%, a 34.16% gap [Q111], establishing that the\nannotation task genuinely requires domain expertise. The expert–GPT-4 gap is 31.82% [Q113],\nindicating substantial headroom. Annotators were selected for native or near-native English\nproficiency [Q27, Q122] and formal FOL education [Q28, Q123]; annotator demographics beyond\nEnglish proficiency and FOL expertise are NOT DOCUMENTED in detail.\n\n### Output Form\nFOLIO evaluates the NL reasoning task via classification accuracy over a three-way categorical\nlabel [Q80], which matches the lab's intended evaluation regime exactly. For the secondary NL-FOL\ntranslation task, two complementary metrics are defined: Syntactic Validity (SynV), a binary\nscore indicating whether all generated FOL formulas pass a syntactic check [Q73, Q74], and\nInference Engine Execution Accuracy (ExcAcc), which feeds translated FOL into the inference\nengine and measures label match against gold [Q75, Q76]. The paper documents that syntactic\nvalidity scores are around 93% for both GPT-3.5-Turbo and GPT-4 [Q96], but execution accuracy\nremains low, indicating models can produce well-formed FOL while failing semantic fidelity [Q97].\nThe inference engine — a Stanford CS22